\begin_layout Standard
We consider the problem of constructing an observer for nonlinear single-output
 systems of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{x}=F(x,u),\quad y=h(x).\label{eq:plant}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 One approach to observer design is to find a nonlinear change of coordinates
 which transforms\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:plant}

\end_inset

 into a system with a linear output map and linear dynamcis driven by a
 nonlinear input-output injection.
 For a system in this so-called observer canonical form, observer design
 is a straightforward task.
 The resulting error dynamics are linear in the transformed coordinates\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{krener83,bestle83}

\end_inset

.
 This approach is often called observer error linearization.
 The concept has been extended to multi-output systems\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{krener85observer,xia88,xia89}

\end_inset

 and to adaptive systems\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{marino1990,marino1995book}

\end_inset

.
 A decentralized design approach based on a block-triangluar observer canonical
 form has been considered in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{rudolph1994,schaffner99ijss}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the conditions of the error linearizability are rather restrictive.
 In\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{kazantzis1998,krener2002}

\end_inset

, the constraint of a linear output map in the canonical form has been removed.
 The work in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{noh2004}

\end_inset

 suggests a dynamic observer error linearization.
 The immersion of a nonlinear system into a higher-dimensional observer
 canonical form is considered in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{back2002,back2005}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even if a system is error linearizable, it is extremely difficult to compute
 the associated coordinate transformation since it requires the solution
 of a system of first order partial differential equations (PDEs).
 An alternative approach to determine the observer canonical form has been
 presented in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{keller86,keller87,li1986,phelps1988,phelps1991}

\end_inset

, where the solution of a scalar higher order PDE is obtained by successive
 integration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, in recent years the problem of an approximate observer error
 linearization attracted some attention.
 For example, the coordinate transformation can be approximated by polynomials
 using Poincar
\family roman
ï¿½
\family default
's normal form theory (see\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{karahan89,krener91poincare,krener2002}

\end_inset

).
 Similarly, one could also employ splines\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{bortoff95,lynch97scl,lynch2001}

\end_inset

.
 Other approaches can be found in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{banaszuk97,nam97,moreno2005syncod}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

