\begin_layout Standard
The error dynamics\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:error-high-gain-typical}

\end_inset

 has the typical form of a high-gain observer\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{thau1973,raghavan1994,rajamani1998}

\end_inset

.
 In fact, if the input-output injection is uniformly Lipschitz in the first
 argument, the constant gain vector\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 can be chosen such that the equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}=0$
\end_inset

 of\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:error-high-gain-typical}

\end_inset

 is exponentially stable\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{roebenack2004nolcos}

\end_inset

.
 Note that the nonlinearities in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:gain-hg-x}

\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a zeroth order Taylor series expansion of the unknown
 output injection 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(z_{n},u)$
\end_inset

 at\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{n}$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}=(A-lc^{T})\tilde{z}+\mathcal{O}(\|\tilde{z}\|)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observer\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:highgain}

\end_inset

 with\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:gain-hg-x}

\end_inset

 is the counterpart of the high-gain observer suggested in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{gauthier92,ciccarella93,dalla-mora1997}

\end_inset

, where we use the observer canonical form instead of the observability
 canonical form.
 This observer also requires a regular observability matrix, which corresponds
 to condition\InsetSpace ~
C1 in Th.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{thm:existence}

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, both observers have structural constraints regarding to the appearanc
e of the input, i.e., condition\InsetSpace ~
C3 corresponds to some extend to the conditions
 given in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{gauthier81}

\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite[Sect.~{III}]{gauthier92}

\end_inset

.
 As for the underlying normal form, the observer in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{gauthier92}

\end_inset

 has weaker existence conditions because C2 is not required there.
 However, the observer\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:highgain}

\end_inset

 with\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:gain-hg-x}

\end_inset

 may be advandageous in a global setting.
 For example, if a system can be transformed into\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:nf}

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha(y)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
\cos y\end{array}\right)\]

\end_inset

by a global transformation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:TS}

\end_inset

, the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0},\ldots,p_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:gain-hg-x}

\end_inset

 can be chosen such that\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:highgain}

\end_inset

 converges globally because the output injection\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is globally Lipschitz\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{roebenack2004nolcos}

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the nonlinearity occurring in the associated observability
 canonical form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\xi}_{1}=\xi_{2},\;\dot{\xi}_{2}=\xi_{3},\;\dot{\xi}_{3}=-\xi_{3}\sin\xi_{1}-\xi_{2}^{2}\cos\xi_{1},\; y=\xi_{1}\]

\end_inset

is not globally Lipschitz, by what global convergence of the observer from\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{gauthier92}

\end_inset

 cannot be guaranteed.
\end_layout

