\begin_layout Standard
The error equation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:error-high-gain-typical}

\end_inset

 coresponds to a standard high-gain observer with the static gain.
 As suggested in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{pertew2005ifac}

\end_inset

 one may extend the observer using a dynamic gain.
 In particular, we use an observer of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\hat{x}}=F(\hat{x},u)+\Pi(\hat{x})\eta,\quad\dot{\xi}=\tilde{A}\xi+\tilde{B}(y-h(\hat{x})),\quad\eta=\tilde{C}\xi+\tilde{D}(y-h(\hat{x}))\]

\end_inset

with\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 according to\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:pde}

\end_inset

 and matrices of appropriate dimensions.
 The error dynamics are governed by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\dot{\tilde{z}}\\
\dot{\xi}\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
A-\tilde{D}c^{T} & -\tilde{C}\\
\tilde{B}c^{T} & \tilde{A}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\tilde{z}\\
\xi\end{array}\right)+\left(\begin{array}{c}
\alpha(z_{n},u)-\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)\\
0\end{array}\right).\]

\end_inset

The matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{C}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

 can be chosen using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

-techniques\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{pertew2005ifac}

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
First Order Approximation with the Extended Luenberger Observer
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Luenberger}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following approach is based directly on\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{bestle83,zeitz87}

\end_inset

.
 Consider a Luenberger-like observer
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{\hat{x}}=F(\hat{x},u)+k_{1}(\hat{x},u)(y-h(\hat{x})),\label{eq:luenberger}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the gain vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{W}\to\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 may also depend in the input\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $u.$
\end_inset

 If the conditions of Th.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{thm:existence}

\end_inset

 hold, the transformation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:TS}

\end_inset

 exists and is applied to\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:luenberger}

\end_inset

.
 In transformed coordiantes, the observation error is now governed by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{\tilde{z}}=A\tilde{z}+\alpha(z_{n},u)-\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)-\left(S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\right)^{-1}k_{1}(S(\hat{z}),u)\,\tilde{z}_{n}.\label{eq:error-luen1}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without the knowledge of the transformation, the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(z_{n},u)$
\end_inset

 must be regarded as unknown even though we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}=y$
\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 We expand 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(z_{n},u)$
\end_inset

 along the reference trajectory\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 of the observer, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(z_{n},u)=\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)+\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)\tilde{z}_{n}+\mathcal{O}(|\tilde{z}_{n}|^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting linearized error equation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:error-luen1}

\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{\tilde{z}}=A\tilde{z}-\left(\left(S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\right)^{-1}k_{1}(S(\hat{z}),u)-\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)\right)c^{T}\tilde{z}+\mathcal{O}(\|\tilde{z}\|^{2})\label{eq:error-luen-linearized}\end{equation}

\end_inset

for any\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 The observer gain\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 will be calculated such that the Jacobian of the linearized error dynamics\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:error-luen-linearized}

\end_inset

 has the characteristic polynomial\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:cp}

\end_inset

 invariant under the operating point.
 This will be achieved by extended Taylor linearization similar to\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{baumann86}

\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{1}(\hat{x},u)=k_{1}(S(\hat{z}),u)=S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\, l+S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\,\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u),\label{eq:k1z}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 one obtains the error differential equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\tilde{z}}=(A-lc^{T})\,\tilde{z}+\mathcal{O}(\|\tilde{z}\|^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Observer gain in original coordinates
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we want to express the observer gain\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:k1z}

\end_inset

 in the original coordinates.
 The diffeomorphisms\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 are inverse to each other.
 Therefore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{*}S_{*}=I$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 denotes the identity matrix.
 From\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:pde}

\end_inset

 we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\prime}(x)\Pi(x)=I$
\end_inset

.
 The columns can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{*}ad_{-f}^{i}v=\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{i+1}}\quad\textrm{for}\quad i=0,\ldots,n-1.\]

\end_inset

Taking condition\InsetSpace ~
C3 into account we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\begin{array}{ccl}
T_{*}ad_{-F}^{n}v & = & T_{*}ad_{-f}^{n}v+T_{*}ad_{-g}ad_{-f}^{n-1}v\\
 & = & T_{*}[-(f+g),ad_{-f}^{n-1}v]\\
 & = & [-Az+\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u),\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}}]\\
 & = & \frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)\end{array}\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ad_{-F}^{n}v(\hat{x},u)=ad_{-f}^{n}v(\hat{x})+ad_{-g}ad_{-f}^{n-1}v(\hat{x},u)=S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\,\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u).\label{eq:ad-n}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Together with\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:gain-hg-z}

\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:gain-hg-x}

\end_inset

 we finally obtain the observer gain 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{1}(\hat{x},u)=p_{0}v(\hat{x})+p_{1}ad_{-f}v(\hat{x})+\cdots+p_{n-1}ad_{-f}^{n-1}v(\hat{x})+ad_{-f}^{n}v(\hat{x})+ad_{-g}ad_{-f}^{n-1}v(\hat{x},u).\label{eq:ackermann}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The dependence of the observer gain\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ackermann}

\end_inset

 on\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is due to the input-dependent vector field\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 occurring in the last summand.
 Eq.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ackermann}

\end_inset

 is a generalization of Ackermann's formula for nonlinear systems\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{bestle83,zeitz87}

\end_inset

.
 The observer\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:luenberger}

\end_inset

 with the gain\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ackermann}

\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
extended Luenberger observer
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that our approach differs slightly from\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{zeitz87}

\end_inset

: Even though\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:plant}

\end_inset

 may be a forced system, the transformation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:TS}

\end_inset

 depends only on the state, but not on the input (due to condition\InsetSpace ~
C3 in
 Th.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{thm:existence}

\end_inset

).
 Moreover, the observer gain\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ackermann}

\end_inset

 does not involve time derivatives of\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Higher Order Approximation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Higher-Order-Approximation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The extended Luenberger observer yields a first order approximation of linear
 error dynamcis.
 To achieve a higher order approximation we consider an observer of the
 form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{\hat{x}}=F(\hat{x},u)+\sum_{i=1}^{N}k_{i}(\hat{x},u)(y-h(\hat{x}))^{i}\label{eq:obs-new}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 with smooth vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},\ldots,k_{N}:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{W}\to\R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If the conditions of Th.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{thm:existence}

\end_inset

 are met, we can apply the transformation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:TS}

\end_inset

 to\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:obs-new}

\end_inset

.
 The associated error dynamics are governed by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{\tilde{z}}=A\tilde{z}+\alpha(z_{n},u)-\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)-\left(S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\right)^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{N}k_{i}(S(\hat{z}),u)\tilde{z}_{n}^{i}.\label{eq:error-dgl-new}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similar as in Section\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Luenberger}

\end_inset

 we consider a series expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(z_{n},u)$
\end_inset

 along the trajectory\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 of the observer, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha(z_{n},u)=\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)+\sum_{i=1}^{N}\frac{\partial^{i}}{i!\,\partial\hat{z}_{n}^{i}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)\,\tilde{z}_{n}^{i}+\mathcal{O}(|\tilde{z}_{n}|^{N+1}).\label{eq:alpha-series-expansion}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Chosing\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 according to\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:k1z}

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\tilde{z}}=(A-lc^{T})\,\tilde{z}+\sum_{i=2}^{N}\left[\left(\frac{\partial^{i}}{i!\,\partial\hat{z}_{n}^{i}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)-\left(S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\right)^{-1}k_{i}(S(\hat{z}),u)\right)\tilde{z}_{n}^{i}\right]+\mathcal{O}(\|\tilde{z}\|^{N+1}).\]

\end_inset

We want to compensate the nonlinear terms up to order\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{i}(\hat{x},u)=\frac{1}{i!}\left.S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\frac{\partial^{i}}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}^{i}}\alpha(\hat{z}_{n},u)\right|_{\hat{z}=T(\hat{x})}\quad\textrm{for}\quad i=2,\ldots,N\label{eq:ki-z-new}\end{equation}

\end_inset

one obtains the desired error dynamics 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{\tilde{z}}=(A-lc^{T})\tilde{z}+\mathcal{O}(\|\tilde{z}\|^{N+1}).\label{eq:error-o-N}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Computation of the additional observer gain vectors
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we will derive a formula to express\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ki-z-new}

\end_inset

 in the original coordinates.
 To simplify the notation we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{(j)}(z_{n},u)=\frac{\partial^{j}}{\partial z_{n}^{j}}\alpha(z_{n},u)$
\end_inset

 and define the vector field\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
w(x)=ad_{-f}^{n-1}v(x).\]

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(j)}(z_{n},u)=ad_{w}^{j-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\quad\textrm{for}\quad j\geq1.\label{eq:claim}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This will be shown by induction.
 Due to\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ad-n}

\end_inset

, Eq.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:claim}

\end_inset

 holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(1)}(z_{n},u)=ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)=ad_{w}^{0}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u).\]

\end_inset

Now, assume\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:claim}

\end_inset

 holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\ldots,i$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}\left(S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(i)}(z_{n},u)\right)=S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(i+1)}(z_{n},u)+\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}S^{\prime}(z)\right)\alpha^{(i)}(z_{n},u).\label{eq:partial}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \eqref{eq:claim}

\end_inset

 holds up to 
\begin_inset Formula $j=i$
\end_inset

, the left hand side of\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \eqref{eq:partial}

\end_inset

 reads as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ars\begin{array}{ccl}
\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}\left(S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(i)}(z_{n},u)\right) & = & \frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}\left.ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\right|_{x=S(z)}\\
 & = & \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x}ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}S(z)\\
 & = & \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x}ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\right)w(x).\end{array}\label{eq:X1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}S^{\prime}(z)=\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}\frac{\partial}{\partial z}S(z)=\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}S(z)=\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\left.w(x)\right|_{x=S(z)}=w^{\prime}(x)S^{\prime}(z).\label{eq:NR}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:claim}

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=i$
\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:NR}

\end_inset

, the second summand on the right hand side of\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:partial}

\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ars\begin{array}{ccl}
\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}S^{\prime}(z)\right)\alpha^{(i)}(z_{n},u) & = & w^{\prime}(x)S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(i)}(z_{n},u)\\
 & = & w^{\prime}(x)S^{\prime}(z)\left(S^{\prime}(z)\right)^{-1}ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\\
 & = & w^{\prime}(x)\, ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u).\end{array}\label{eq:X2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

With\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:partial}

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:X1}

\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:X2}

\end_inset

 we get
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ars\begin{array}{ccl}
S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(i+1)}(z_{n},u) & = & \frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}\left(S^{\prime}(z)\alpha^{(i)}(z_{n},u)\right)-\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial z_{n}}S^{\prime}(z)\right)\alpha^{(i)}(z_{n},u)\\
 & = & \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x}ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\right)w(x)-w^{\prime}(x)\, ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\\
 & = & ad_{w}^{i}ad_{-F}^{n}v(x,u)\end{array}\]

\end_inset

which proves\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:claim}

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the observer gain\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ki-z-new}

\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{i}(\hat{x},u)=\frac{1}{i!}ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-F}^{n}v(\hat{x},u)=\frac{1}{i!}\left(ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-f}^{n}v(\hat{x})+ad_{w}^{i-1}ad_{-g}ad_{-f}^{n-1}v(\hat{x},u)\right)\label{eq:ki-x-new}\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the observer gain\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

 of a second order approximation is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
k_{2}(\hat{x},u)=\frac{1}{2}ad_{w}ad_{-F}^{n}v(\hat{x},u)=\frac{1}{2}[w,ad_{-F}^{n}v](\hat{x},u)=\frac{1}{2}[ad_{-f}^{n-1}v,ad_{-f}^{n}v+ad_{-g}ad_{-f}^{n-1}v](\hat{x},u).\]

\end_inset

In case of an unforced system, this observer gain simplifies to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{2}(\hat{x})=\frac{1}{2}[ad_{-f}^{n-1}v,ad_{-f}^{n}v](\hat{x}),\label{eq:k2-unforced}\end{equation}

\end_inset

see\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{roebenack-gamm2004}

\end_inset

.
 It has already been noted earlier that the output injection 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

 of an unforced system is linear in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 if\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:k2-unforced}

\end_inset

 is identical to the zero vector\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite[Prop.~2]{isidori3}

\end_inset

.
