\begin_layout Standard
If the linearization of\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:plant}

\end_inset

 at\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is observable, a trivial decomposition into\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:plant-fg}

\end_inset

 can be achieved by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=F^{\prime}(x_{0},0)(x-x_{0})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,u)=F(x,u)-f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 By this, we split system\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:plant}

\end_inset

 into a linear and a nonlinear part, and design the observer by classical
 high-gain techniques\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{thau1973,rajamani1998}

\end_inset

.
 However, Theorem\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{thm:aocf}

\end_inset

 addresses more general decompositions of\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:plant}

\end_inset

 into two nonlinear terms.
 If the vector field\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is nonlinear, the computation of the resulting transformation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:TS}

\end_inset

 may still be complicated.
 In this case, we could use the approximation techniques derived in Sect.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Approximation-of-observers}

\end_inset

.
 In particular, we suggest the observer\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:obs-new}

\end_inset

, whose gain vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},\ldots,k_{N}$
\end_inset

 are computed by\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ackermann}

\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ki-x-new}

\end_inset

.
 A similar calculation as in Sect.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Approximation-of-observers}

\end_inset

 reveals that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
k_{1}(\hat{x},u)=\left.S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\, l+S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\,\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}}\hat{\alpha}(\hat{z}_{n},H\hat{z},u)\right|_{\hat{z}=T(\hat{x})}\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula \[
k_{i}(\hat{x},u)=\frac{1}{i!}\left.S^{\prime}(\hat{z})\frac{\partial^{i}}{\partial\hat{z}_{n}^{i}}\hat{\alpha}(\hat{z}_{n},H\hat{z},u)\right|_{\hat{z}=T(\hat{x})}\quad\textrm{for}\quad i=2,\ldots,N.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, if the conditions of Theorem\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{thm:aocf}

\end_inset

 are fulfilled, the observers\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:highgain}

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:luenberger}

\end_inset

 and\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:obs-new}

\end_inset

 are Taylor approximations of the observer\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:aocf}

\end_inset

.
 In particular, we obtain the error dynamics 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\tilde{z}}=(A-lc^{T})\tilde{z}+\mathcal{O}(\|\tilde{z}_{n}\|^{N+1},\| H\tilde{z}\|).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

