\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:ackermann}

\end_inset

 of the extended Luenberger observer\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \prettyref{eq:luenberger}

\end_inset

 reads as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{1}(\hat{x})=\left(\begin{array}{c}
p_{1}-\hat{x}_{1}+1\\
p_{0}+p_{1}(1-\hat{x}_{1}^{2})-2\hat{x}_{1}^{2}+\hat{x}_{1}^{4}\end{array}\right).\label{eq:k1-vdp}\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a higher order approximation we obtain the gain vectors
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{2}(\hat{x})=\left(\begin{array}{c}
-\hat{x}_{1}\\
\hat{x}_{1}(\hat{x}_{1}^{2}-1)\end{array}\right),\quad k_{3}(\hat{x})=\frac{1}{3}\left(\begin{array}{c}
-1\\
\hat{x}_{1}^{2}-1\end{array}\right),\quad k_{j}(\hat{x})=\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\end{array}\right)\quad\textrm{for}\quad j\geq4.\label{eq:k234-vdp}\end{equation}

\end_inset

In particular, the series expansion has only a finite number of terms.
